{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:28:23.658Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Discovering Missing Links**\n\nI've made a key discovery: interactive tools are wrapped in `ToolPageShell`. However, I've identified a discrepancy. The `/build/blueprint` tool, specifically its `page.tsx`, does not appear to utilize this wrapper, which is a key component to note. This needs some further investigation.\n\n\n**Confirming Page Integration**\n\nI've confirmed a direct path to integrate the blueprint page with `ToolPageShell`. Implementing it will offer the animated background and telemetry bar, aligning it with other tools. This seems straightforward - just import `ToolPageShell` and use it as a wrapper. This will be the next step to review!\n\n\n**Refining Integration Approach**\n\nI'm now considering the best way to integrate the `ToolPageShell` with the blueprint tool. Initially, I thought about modifying `/build/blueprint/page.tsx`, but now I'm leaning toward updating `BlueprintGenerator.tsx` to handle wrapping and use `WizardStepperSystem` within it. I want to build out custom steps inside `BlueprintGenerator.tsx` using the `WizardStepperSystem` structure. This will keep the layout clean!\n\n\n**Defining State Integration**\n\nI've been figuring out how to manage additional state within `WizardStepperSystem` for our blueprint tool, specifically `customChallengeText`. My solution is to incorporate `customChallengeText` into the `initialAnswers` object. This looks like the right approach, given that we can add the field to our current `BlueprintAnswers` type definition. Let's see how that works.\n\n\n**Clarifying Data Structure**\n\nI've determined the cleanest way to integrate the new state. I can either create a local type or modify `BlueprintAnswers`. Checking `lib/blueprint-data.ts` confirmed that adding `customChallengeText?: string` to `BlueprintAnswers` is a clean way to go, but I'll create `BlueprintWizardData` which extends `BlueprintAnswers` and includes `customChallengeText`, `otpSent`, and `enteredOtp`. This design keeps all the state consolidated within the wizard, which passes it to each rendered step. This seems really clean!\n\n\n**Designing Initial Wizard Step**\n\nI'm now focusing on designing the first step of the wizard, which involves defining the user's business context. I'll need to render fields for industry vertical, company size, and region. I'm planning to use clean option buttons for industry vertical, clickable scale buttons for organization scale, and a grid for target budget and geography, all styled with Next/Tailwind inputs. I'll be sure to include validation to ensure that both industry and company size are selected. I'll make the initial options `Banking`, `Retail`, `Healthcare`, `Manufacturing`, `Tech`, and `Other` for industry; `<100`, `100-1000`, `1000-10000`, `10000+` for company size. I'll also add in `Under $100k`, `$100k-$500k`, `$500k-$2M`, `$2M+` for the budget ranges, and `North America`, `Europe`, `APAC`, `LATAM`, and `Global` for region.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Validation and Input**\n\nI'm now implementing validation for the first wizard step, focusing on strategic priorities. I'll make sure the `topPriorities` field has between one and three selections. I'm working with a multi-select card list, with options like `Cost Reduction`, `Productivity`, and others. It will have simple checkbox buttons that enforce this limit!\nI'm also working on rendering the AI Maturity Stage in the next step, using option cards for easy selection.\n\n\n**Defining Next Wizard Steps**\n\nI'm now designing the next wizard steps. Step 4, \"Data and Leadership,\" will involve selecting data integration readiness and leadership commitment level, with validation to ensure both are selected. I'll render these options as beautiful cards, with choices for \"Data Readiness\" (Highly fragmented, Partially connected, Mostly integrated, Fully integrated) and \"Leadership Commitment\" (Not Discussed, Exploring, Budget Approved, Executive Mandate). Step 5 will then define the sovereign bottleneck.\n\n\n**Constructing Wizard Step Elements**\n\nI'm now building out the final verification step, step 6. I've designed validation that checks for a valid, non-empty email. Additionally, I'll validate the simulated OTP flow to ensure the correct code \"123456\" is entered. I'm focusing on rendering a clean email input field and an OTP input field, all styled using our design system.\n\n\n**Refining OTP Input Logic**\n\nI'm now implementing the OTP input logic for the final verification step. If the user hasn't requested a PIN, I show a \"Request Access PIN\" button. If they *have* requested it, I display an amber info box explaining the simulated flow and a suggested OTP of \"123456.\" Then, I render the actual OTP input field with a note on how \"Sovereign Compile\" generates the custom report. This input flow is now complete!\n\n\n**Verifying Visual Consistency**\n\nI'm now diving into the final rendering of the blueprint report. My focus is on ensuring visual consistency and a premium feel, matching GFF's branding. I need to make sure `renderResult` produces a report that includes the circular score ring, recommended solution details, business impact, roadmap, and opportunity nodes, all beautifully styled. I'm also now specifically focused on preserving the existing custom SVG icons in `BlueprintGenerator.tsx`. I need to review which icons were used for the industry verticals.\n\n\n**Refining Icon Rendering**\n\nI'm now carefully rendering the SVG icons for industry verticals within the report. I'm focusing on ensuring consistent styling and correct color palettes for each icon. I've added a switch statement to ensure the correct icons are rendered based on the selected industry. I need to make sure each case returns an SVG icon with the appropriate class names for styling, and ensuring correct colors. I'm reviewing the existing icons and incorporating them into the report.\n\n\n\n**Verifying Existing Icon Usage**\n\nI'm now making sure all icon options are accounted for. I've found a couple of files to check. I realized there are differences. I also need to verify that `BlueprintGenerator.tsx` is only using the existing icons, and that they are correctly rendered within the report. Additionally, I'll be checking `page.tsx`, to make sure that these icons are being consistently utilized across the application.\n\n\n\n**Confirming Wrapper Integration**\n\nNow I'm confirming that the `app/build/blueprint/page.tsx` directly imports `ToolPageShell` and wraps the `BlueprintGenerator` component. Following the pattern observed in `app/build/assessment/page.tsx`, this will allow the blueprint page to display a consistent wrapper. It is the best choice to render using this strategy!\n\n\n\n**Confirming Tool Integration**\n\nI'm now integrating the `ToolPageShell` into `BlueprintGenerator.tsx`. I will wrap the entire generator component within the shell, as this appears to be the most straightforward and maintainable approach. I've double-checked that `app/build/blueprint/page.tsx` is a client component, ensuring safe and correct integration. Furthermore, I've confirmed that this change aligns with the tool's standard structure, and will not impact existing blueprint logic. I'm verifying that the landing page will remain untouched, along with the blueprint scoring rules. This approach lets us centralize all blueprint layouts with the `showContact` prop set.\n\n\n**Refining Contextual Elements**\n\nI'm now focusing on cleanly integrating budget and geography selection within Step 1 (Organization Context). We'll use grid select layouts to ensure a professional design. The `WizardStepperSystem` already handles the desired self-assessment tool look. I've confirmed that the imports in `BlueprintGenerator.tsx` align with the approach.\n\n\n"}}
